'''Kajiwara Clan''' (梶原氏) is a {{ill|Japanese clan|ja|日本の氏族|12=draft}}. The most notable lineage is a branch of the {{ill|Ōba clan|ja|大庭氏|12=draft}}, which descends from the {{ill|Kamakura clan|ja|鎌倉氏|12=draft}}, itself part of the {{ill|Kammu Heishi|ja|桓武平氏|12=draft}} lineage, one of the {{ill|Bandō Hachihei|ja|坂東八平氏|12=draft}}.

== Taira Lineage of the Kajiwara Clan ==
{{日本の氏族
|家名= Kajiwara Clan
|家紋= Maruni-narabiya.jpg
|家紋名称= Maruni Narabiya (丸に並び矢)
|本姓= {{ill|Kammu Heishi|ja|桓武平氏|12=draft}} - {{ill|Taira no Yoshifumi|ja|平良文|12=draft}} lineage, branch of the {{ill|Kamakura clan|ja|鎌倉氏|12=draft}} via the {{ill|Ōba clan|ja|大庭氏|12=draft}}
|家祖= {{ill|Kajiwara Kagehisa (Heian period)|ja|梶原景久 (平安時代)|12=draft}}
|種別= {{ill|Samurai|ja|武家|12=draft}}
|出身地= {{ill|Kamakura District, Sagami Province|ja|相模国鎌倉郡|12=draft}} - {{ill|Kajiwara (Kamakura)|ja|梶原|12=draft}}
|人物= {{ill|Kajiwara Kagetoki|ja|梶原景時|12=draft}}<br>{{ill|Kajiwara Kagesue|ja|梶原景季|12=draft}}<br>{{ill|Kajiwara Kagehisa|ja|梶原景久|12=draft}}<br>{{ill|Dan Tadamasu|ja|団忠正|12=draft}}
|根拠地= Sagami Province
|支流= {{ill|Sakawa clan|ja|酒匂氏|12=draft}} (Samurai)<br>{{ill|Yakuno clan|ja|役野氏|12=draft}} (Samurai)<br>{{ill|Ogino clan|ja|荻野氏|12=draft}} (Samurai)<br>{{ill|Karakawa clan|ja|唐桑氏|12=draft}} (Samurai)<br>{{ill|Kamisaka clan|ja|鎌倉氏|12=draft}} (Samurai)<br>{{ill|Utsugi clan|ja|宇津木氏|12=draft}} (Samurai)<br>{{ill|Dan clan|ja|団氏|12=draft}} (Samurai) and others
}}

The clan originated with {{ill|Kajiwara Kagehisa|ja|梶原景久|12=draft}}, the eldest son of {{ill|Kamakura Kagemichi|ja|鎌倉景通|12=draft}} of the {{ill|Ōba clan|ja|大庭氏|12=draft}}, who took the name "Kajiwara" from their territory in {{ill|Kajiwara, Kamakura|ja|梶原|12=draft}}, Sagami Province. The clan rose to prominence during the time of {{ill|Kajiwara Kagetoki|ja|梶原景時|12=draft}}, though their fortunes later declined.

== Overview ==
Under the leadership of {{ill|Kajiwara Kagetoki|ja|梶原景時|12=draft}}, the clan flourished. In pp80, when {{ill|Minamoto no Yoritomo|ja|源頼朝|12=draft}} raised his army, Kagetoki initially opposed him alongside {{ill|Ōba Kagechika|ja|大庭景親|12=draft}} during the {{ill|Battle of Ishibashiyama|ja|石橋山の戦い|12=draft}}. However, Kagetoki allowed Yoritomo to escape, earning the latter's favor.

The Kajiwara clan supported Yoritomo in the {{ill|Genpei War|ja|源平合戦|12=draft}}, achieving prominence during the {{ill|Battle of Dan-no-ura|ja|壇ノ浦の戦い|12=draft}} in pp85, which marked the downfall of the {{ill|Taira clan|ja|伊勢平氏|12=draft}}. However, Kagetoki's acceptance of court appointments with {{ill|Minamoto no Yoshitsune|ja|源義経|12=draft}} angered Yoritomo. Despite this, the Kajiwara continued to serve loyally during the {{ill|Ōshū Campaign|ja|奥州合戦|12=draft}}.

After Yoritomo's death, opposition from the {{ill|Hōjō clan|ja|北条氏|12=draft}} and others led to Kagetoki's downfall in the {{ill|Incident of Kajiwara Kagetoki|ja|梶原景時の変|12=draft}}. His descendants, however, continued to serve in various capacities across Japan.

=== Prominent Branches ===
* '''Karakawa Kajiwara Clan'''
''' Centered in {{ill|Karakuwa, Kesennuma|ja|宮城県気仙沼市唐桑町|12=draft}}. This settlement includes over 100 households bearing the Kajiwara name, making it the largest concentration of the surname in Japan. The branch descends from {{ill|Kajiwara Kagemasa|ja|梶原景実|12=draft}}, Kagetoki's brother, who established {{ill|Kajiwara Shrine|ja|梶原神社|12=draft}} and {{ill|Hayama Shrine|ja|早馬神社|12=draft}} in the region.

* '''Shimotsuke Kajiwara Clan'''
''' Descendants of {{ill|Kajiwara Kagesue|ja|梶原景季|12=draft}} who sought refuge with the {{ill|Utsunomiya clan|ja|宇都宮氏|12=draft}}.

* '''Sanuki Kajiwara Clan'''
''' Descendants of Kagetoki's third son, Kagemochi, who became sea pirates in {{ill|Sanuki Province|ja|讃岐国|12=draft}} before serving as retainers to the {{ill|Kuroda Domain|ja|黒田藩|12=draft}}.

* '''Musashi Kajiwara Clan'''
''' Another branch of Kagemochi's descendants settled in {{ill|Musashi Province|ja|武蔵国|12=draft}}, serving as retainers of the {{ill|Kamakura shogunate|ja|鎌倉幕府|12=draft}}.

* '''Owari Kajiwara Clan'''
''' Descendants of Kagetoki's second and third sons, Kageyuki and Kagemochi, who settled in {{ill|Owari Province|ja|尾張国|12=draft}} and served notable figures such as {{ill|Oda Nobunaga|ja|織田信長|12=draft}}.

=== Historical Heads ===
1. {{ill|Kajiwara Kagehisa|ja|梶原景久|12=draft}} (Founder)
2. {{ill|Kajiwara Kagenaga|ja|梶原景長|12=draft}} (Second head)
3. {{ill|Kajiwara Kagekiyo|ja|梶原景清|12=draft}} (Third head)
4. {{ill|Kajiwara Kagetoki|ja|梶原景時|12=draft}} (Fourth head)
5. {{ill|Kajiwara Tomokage|ja|梶原朝景|12=draft}} (Fifth head)

=== Related Clans ===
* {{ill|Sakawa clan|ja|酒匂氏|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Yakuno clan|ja|役野氏|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Ogino clan|ja|荻野氏|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Kamisaka clan|ja|鎌倉氏|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Utsugi clan|ja|宇津木氏|12=draft}}

